gn=center|N/A\n|[[Richmond, Virginia]], United States\n|\n{{end}}\n\n===Mixed martial arts exhibition record===\n{{MMA exhibition record box\n| draws= \n| nc= \n| ko-wins= \n| ko-losses= 1\n| sub-wins= 1\n| sub-losses= \n| dec-wins= 1\n| dec-losses= \n| dq-wins= \n| dq-losses= \n| other-wins= \n| other-losses= \n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 2\u20131\n| [[John Dodson (fighter)|John Dodson]]\n| KO (punches)\n| [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Bisping vs. Team Miller]]\n| {{dts|2011|November|16|format=mdy}} (airdate)\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 1:00\n| [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], United States\n| {{small|Semi-finals.}}\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 2\u20130\n| Josh Ferguson\n| Decision (unanimous)\n| [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Bisping vs. Team Miller]]\n| {{dts|2011|November|2|format=mdy}} (airdate)\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 5:00\n| Las Vegas, Nevada, United States\n| {{small|Quarter-finals.}}\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 1\u20130\n| Carson Beebe\n| Submission (neck crank)\n| [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Bisping vs. Team Miller]]\n| {{dts|2011|September|21|format=mdy}} (airdate)\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 4:19\n| Las Vegas, Nevada, United States\n| {{small|Preliminary bout.}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Bare knuckle record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n|ko-wins=3\n|ko-losses=\n|sub-wins=\n|sub-losses=\n|dec-wins=2\n|dec-losses=\n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|5-0\n|[[Charles Bennett (fighter)|Charles Bennett]]\n|TKO (hand injury)\n|Bare Knuckle FC 9\n|{{dts|2019|November|16}}\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|2:00\n|[[Biloxi, Mississippi]], United States\n|\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|4\u20130\n|Reggie Barnett, Jr.\n|Decision (unanimous)\n|Bare Knuckle FC 6\n|{{dts|2019|June|22}}\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|2:00\n|[[Tampa, Florida]], United States \n|{{small|Lightweight Tournament Final}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|3-0\n|Abdiel Velazquez\n|TKO (punches)\n|Bare Knuckle FC 5\n|{{dts|2019|April|6}}\n|align=center|4\n|align=center|0:58\n|[[Biloxi, Mississippi]], United States\n|{{small|Lightweight Tournament Semifinal}}\n|-\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|2\u20130\n|Matt Murphy\n|Decision (unanimous)\n|[[2018 in Bare Knuckle Fighting Championship#Bare Knuckle Fighting Championship 3: The Takeover|BKFC 3: The Takeover]]\n|{{dts|2018|October|20}}\n|align=center|5\n|align=center|2:00\n|[[Biloxi, Mississippi]], USA\n|\n|- \n|{{yes2}}Win\n|align=center|1-0\n|[[Nick Mamalis]]\n|TKO (punches)\n|[[2018 in Bare Knuckle Fighting Championship#Bare Knuckle Fighting Championship 1: The Beginning|BKFC 1: The Beginning]]\n|{{dts|2018|June|2}}\n|align=center|2\n|align=center|1:41\n|[[Cheyenne, Wyoming]], USA\n|\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{UFC|Johnny-Bedford}}\n* {{Sherdog}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bedford, Johnny}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial artists from Ohio]]\n[[Category:Bantamweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:American practitioners of Brazilian jiu-jitsu]]\n[[Category:American male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:People from Woodville, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Bare-knuckle boxers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American sport wrestler and martial artist}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Johnny Bedford\n| other_names     = Brutal\n| image           =\n| image_size      = 200px\n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| birth_name      = John Charles Bedford\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1983|1|6}}\n| birth_place     = [[Woodville, Ohio]], United States\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       =\n| nationality     = [[People of the United States|American]]\n| height          = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| weight          = {{convert|140.1|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| weight_class    = [[Featherweight (MMA)|Featherweight]]<br>[[Bantamweight (MMA)|Bantamweight]]\n| reach           = {{convert|71.0|in|cm|abbr=on}}\n| style           = \n| stance          = Orthodox\n| fighting_out_of = [[Fort Worth, Texas]], United States<br>[[Colleyville, Texas]], United States\n| team            = Fitness Fight Factory\n| rank            = ''Black belt [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]]''\n| wrestling       = ''NCAA Division I [[Collegiate wrestling|Wrestling]]''\n| years_active    = 2003\u2013''present''\n| mma_kowin       = 10\n| mma_subwin      = 9\n| mma_decwin      = 4\n| mma_koloss      = 2\n| mma_subloss     = 11\n| mma_decloss     = 1\n| mma_draw        = 1\n| mma_nc          = 1\n| url             = [http://www.brutaljohnnybedford.com Official Website]\n| sherdog         = 19717\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         =\n}}\n\n'''John Charles \"Johnny\" Bedford''' (born January 6, 1983) is an American [[mixed martial artist]] currently competing in the [[Bantamweight (MMA)|Bantamweight]] division. A professional competitor since 2003, he has formerly competed for the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]], [[Bellator MMA|Bellator]], the [[Legacy Fighting Alliance]], and was a competitor on [[Spike TV]]'s [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Bisping vs. Team Miller]]\n\n==Background==\nBedford was born and raised in [[Woodville, Ohio]]. At the age of five, Bedford began wrestling year round. He and his family would travel all over the Midwest so Bedford could compete in various wrestling tournaments. He went on to wrestle for [[Woodmore High School]], where his father was the head wrestling coach. Bedford was a three-time state qualifier, placed in the state tournament twice, and during his senior year finished third in the state tournament with a record of 51-1.<ref name=\"Bio\" /> After graduating from Woodmore he enrolled at [[Cleveland State University]]. At Cleveland State, Bedford was on the wrestling team for a year and a half before he was removed from the school (as well as the wrestling squad) before later making the transition to a career in [[mixed martial arts]].<ref name=\"Bio\">[http://www.brutaljohnnybedford.com/career.html Official Johnny Bedford Website, BRUTAL Johnny Bedford]. Brutaljohnnybedford.com (2011-09-21). Retrieved on 2011-12-08.</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\n===Amateur career===\nBedford began fighting in 2003 because he was a self-proclaimed \"tough guy\" that just wanted to prove how tough he was. Bedford proclaims his first six amateur fights took place in a barn where the promoter just asked the audience who wanted to fight and then would match them up by who was closest to one another's weight. With no commission in Ohio at the time, the fights were not sanctioned.<ref>[https://www.usatoday.com/sports/mma/post/2011-09-21/johnny-bedfore-the-ultimate-fighter-interview/548200/1 'TUF' 14: Meet bantamweight hopeful Johnny Bedford]. Usatoday.com (2011-09-21). Retrieved on 2011-12-08.</ref>\n\n===Early professional career===\nAfter a successful amateur career, Bedford took a year and half off from fighting before being offered his first professional fight in 2006 for $200. With no income, Bedford took the fight on short notice and lost via submission in the first round. Bedford began fighting more frequently and by the end of 2009 Bedford held a 13\u20138\u20131 record.\n\n===Bellator===\nBedford was invited to fight for [[Bellator MMA|Bellator]] in 2010. The fight took place at [[Bellator 19]] in [[Grand Prairie, Texas]] on May 20, 2010. Bedford fought and defeated Jared Lopez via third-round TKO.\n\n===Post-Bellator===\nAt King of Kombat 9: Resurrection, Bedford fought future UFC fighter, [[Edwin Figueroa]]. Bedford lost the fight via TKO in the opening of the second round, handing Bedford his only knockout loss in his career. Four months later he bounced back with a first round submission over [[World Extreme Cagefighting|WEC]] veteran [[Frank Gomez]].\n\n===The Ultimate Fighter===\nIn 2011, Bedford had signed with the UFC to compete on [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Bisping vs. Team Miller]]. In the first episode, Bedford fought Carson Beebe to gain entry into the ''Ultimate Fighter'' house. Bedford defeated Beebe in the first round via submission (neck crank). He was selected as a part of Team Mayhem.\n\nBedford then fought Josh Ferguson in the third episode and won by unanimous decision after using his superior size to take down and control Ferguson.\n\nIn the semi-finals Bedford pleaded for the fight against Team Mayhem teammate, [[John Dodson (fighter)|John Dodson]]. The coaches and [[Dana White]] agreed with the fight, and matched the two up. After a closely contested first round, Bedford lost after being knocked unconscious one minute into round two. When asked if he knew where he was immediately after the fight, Bedford replied, \"I'm in Ohio\"; his homestate.\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nThough he did not win the show, Bedford signed an exclusive contract with the UFC. He officially made his UFC debut on December 3, 2011 at [[The Ultimate Fighter 14 Finale]] against ''Ultimate Fighter'' castmate [[Louis Gaudinot]]. Bedford dominated the entirety of the fight and won in the third round via TKO after hitting several knees to Gaudinot's body.\n\nBedford was expected to face [[Eddie Wineland]] on January 28, 2012 at [[UFC on Fox 2]], replacing [[Demetrious Johnson (fighter)|Demetrious Johnson]] who had been pulled from the bout to be a participant in the UFC's inaugural [[Flyweight (MMA)|Flyweight]] tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/26499/ufc-adds-flyweights-johnson-vs-mccall-benavidez-vs-urushitani-at-ufc-on-fx-2.mma |title=UFC adds flyweights: Johnson vs. McCall, Benavidez vs. Urushitani at UFC on FX 2 |publisher=mmajunkie.com |date=December 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120107201557/http://mmajunkie.com/news/26499/ufc-adds-flyweights-johnson-vs-mccall-benavidez-vs-urushitani-at-ufc-on-fx-2.mma |archivedate=January  7, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/26536/tuf-14-fighter-johnny-bedford-takes-ufc-on-fox-2-slot-against-eddie-wineland.mma |title='TUF 14' fighter Johnny Bedford takes UFC on FOX 2 slot against Eddie Wineland |publisher=mmajunkie.com |date=December 14, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108000248/http://mmajunkie.com/news/26536/tuf-14-fighter-johnny-bedford-takes-ufc-on-fox-2-slot-against-eddie-wineland.mma |archivedate=January  8, 2012 }}</ref>  However, Wineland himself was forced out of the bout with an injury and replaced by promotional newcomer [[Mitch Gagnon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmafrenzy.com/26996/mitch-gagnon-steps-in-against-johnny-bedford-at-ufc-on-fox-2/|title=Mitch Gagnon Steps In Against Johnny Bedford at UFC on Fox 2 |publisher=mmafrenzy.com|date=December 28, 2011}}</ref>  On January 25, 2012, the UFC announced the bout was cancelled due to Gagnon's alleged visa issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cagejunkies.com/2012/01/ufc-on-fox-2-bedfordgagnon-off-joey-beltran-vs-lavar-johnson-now-televised-on-fuel-tv/ |title=Bedford/Gagnon off |publisher=MMAJunkie.com |date=January 25, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520091843/http://cagejunkies.com/2012/01/ufc-on-fox-2-bedfordgagnon-off-joey-beltran-vs-lavar-johnson-now-televised-on-fuel-tv/ |archivedate=May 20, 2012 }}</ref> Bedford received his show-money of $8,000 dollars, despite the cancellation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmamania.com/2012/1/25/2732787/the-mitch-gagnon-vs-johnny-bedford-fight-scheduled-for-ufc-on-fox-2|title=The Mitch Gagnon vs. Johnny Bedford fight scheduled for UFC on Fox 2 has been cancelled due to visa issues|publisher=MMAMania.com|date=January 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBedford was expected to face [[Nick Denis]] at [[UFC on Fox 3]] on May 5, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmainterplay.com/ufc-news/ufc-on-fox-3-adds-johnny-bedford-vs-nick-denis-dennis-bermudez-vs-pablo-garza-57047/|title=UFC on FOX 3 adds Johnny Bedford vs. Nick Denis, Dennis Bermudez vs. Pablo Garza|publisher=mmainterplay.com|date=February 17, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221120432/http://www.mmainterplay.com/ufc-news/ufc-on-fox-3-adds-johnny-bedford-vs-nick-denis-dennis-bermudez-vs-pablo-garza-57047/|archivedate=February 21, 2012}}</ref>  However, Bedford was forced out of the bout with an injury and replaced by [[Roland Delorme]].<ref name=\"BedfordOut/DelormeIn\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/ufc/2012/4/18/2958014/roland-delorme-replaces-johnny-bedford-against-nick-denis-at-ufc-on|title=Roland Delorme Replaces Johnny Bedford Against Nick Denis at UFC on FOX 3 |work=mmafighting.com |last=Helwani |first=Ariel |date=April 18, 2012 |accessdate=April 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter nearly a year off due to various injuries, Bedford returned on December 15, 2012 to face [[Marcos Vinicius (fighter)|Marcos Vinicius]] at [[The Ultimate Fighter: Team Carwin vs. Team Nelson Finale]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mmajunkie.com/news/30912/the-ultimate-fighter-16-finale-adds-khabilov-pichel-duran-viana-bedford-vinicius.mma |title=The Ultimate Fighter 16 Finale adds Bedford-Vinicius |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |date=October 2, 2012 |accessdate=October 2, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004050354/http://mmajunkie.com/news/30912/the-ultimate-fighter-16-finale-adds-khabilov-pichel-duran-viana-bedford-vinicius.mma |archivedate=October 4, 2012 }}</ref> He won the fight via KO in the second round.\n\nBedford was expected to face [[Erik Perez]] on April 27, 2013 at [[UFC 159]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/03/unbeaten-135-pounders-johnny-bedford-and-erik-perez-meet-at-ufc-159 |title=Unbeaten 135-pounders Johnny Bedford and Erik Perez meet at UFC 159 |publisher=MMAjunkie.com |date=March 6, 2013 |accessdate=March 6, 2013}}</ref>  However, Perez pulled out of the bout just days before the event citing an injury and was replaced by [[Bryan Caraway]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/04/erik-perez-out-johnny-bedford-now-meets-bryan-caraway-at-ufc-159|title=Erik Perez out, Johnny Bedford now meets Bryan Caraway at UFC 159|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2013-04-22|accessdate=2013-04-22}}</ref> He lost the back-and-forth fight via submission in the third round.\n\nBedford was expected to face [[Hugo Viana (fighter)|Hugo Viana]] on September 4, 2013 at [[UFC Fight Night 28]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportv.globo.com/site/combate/noticia/2013/07/hugo-wolverine-enfrenta-johnny-bedford-no-ufc-de-belo-horizonte.html |title=Hugo Wolverine enfrenta Johnny Bedford no UFC de Belo Horizonte (Brazilian Portuguese)|publisher=sportv.globo.com |author=Alexandre Fernandes|date=2013-07-12 |accessdate=2012-07-12}}</ref>  However, Bedford pulled out of the bout citing an injury and was replaced by [[Wilson Reis]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2013/8/21/4643686/wilson-reis-replaces-injured-johny-bedford-against-hugo-viana-at-ufn |title=Wilson Reis replaces injured Johny Bedford against Hugo Viana at UFN 28|publisher=mmafighting.com |author=Guilherme Cruz|date=2013-08-21 |accessdate=2012-08-21}}</ref>\n\nBedford faced [[Rani Yahya]] on April 11, 2014 at [[UFC Fight Night 39]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2014/2/10/5397268/rani-yahya-drops-to-135-pounds-meets-johnny-bedford-at-ufn-39-card-in|title=Rani Yahya drops to 135 pounds, meets Johnny Bedford at UFN 39 card in Abu Dhabi|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Guilherme Cruz|accessdate=2014-02-10|date=2014-02-10}}</ref>  The bout ended in a No Contest as an accidental clash of heads rendered Yahya unable to protect himself, forcing a referee stoppage at 0:39 of round 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/04/ufc-fight-night-39-results-johnny-bedford-vs-rani-yahya-ends-in-39-second-no-contest/|title=UFC Fight Night 39 results: Johnny Bedford vs. Rani Yahya ends in 39-second no-contest|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Ben Fowlkes|accessdate=2014-04-11|date=2014-04-11}}</ref> Bedford argued vociferously that the accidental clash of heads should have been ruled a TKO victory in his favor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2014/4/11/5605000/johnny-bedford-knocks-rani-yahya-out-with-headbutt-loses-mind-at-no|title=Johnny Bedford knocks Rani Yahya out with headbutt, loses mind at 'no contest' announcement|publisher=bloodyelbow.com|author=Brent Brookhouse|accessdate=2014-04-11|date=2014-04-11}}</ref>\n\nA rematch with Yahya was expected to take place on June 28, 2014 at [[UFC Fight Night 44]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/04/rani-yahya-and-johnny-bedford-get-rematch-at-ufc-fight-night-44/|title=Rani Yahya and Johnny Bedford get rematch at UFC Fight Night 44|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|accessdate=2014-04-21|date=2014-04-21}}</ref>  However, Yahya was forced out of the bout and replaced by Cody Gibson.<ref name=\"YahyaOut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tatame.com.br/rani-yahya-esta-fora-da-luta-contra-desafeto-johnny-bedford-ultimate-anuncia-substituto/|title=Rani Yahya est\u00e1 fora da luta contra \u2018desafeto\u2019 Johnny Bedford; Ultimate anuncia substituto (Brazilian Portuguese)|publisher=tatame.com.br|author=Staff|accessdate=2014-05-20|date=2014-05-20|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140520215705/http://www.tatame.com.br/rani-yahya-esta-fora-da-luta-contra-desafeto-johnny-bedford-ultimate-anuncia-substituto/|archivedate=2014-05-20}}</ref> For the second time in a row, his fight ended under somewhat controversial circumstances as Bedford was dropped by punches from Gibson and the fight was stopped by the referee just as Bedford appeared to be regaining consciousness, resulting in a first-round TKO loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/06/ufc-fight-night-44-results-cody-gibson-stops-irate-johnny-bedford-in-38-seconds|title=UFC Fight Night 44 results: Cody Gibson stops irate Johnny Bedford in 38 seconds|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Ben Fowlkes|accessdate=2014-06-28|date=2014-06-28}}</ref>\n\nThe rescheduled rematch with [[Rani Yahya]] eventually took place on September 13, 2014 at [[UFC Fight Night 51]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Rani-YahyaJohnny-Bedford-Rematch-Set-for-UFC-Fight-Night-on-Sept-13-71061|title=Rani Yahya-Johnny Bedford Rematch Set for UFC Fight Night on Sept. 13|publisher=sherdog.com|author=C.J. Tuttle|accessdate=2014-07-24|date=2014-07-24}}</ref> Yahya won via submission in the second round, and Bedford was subsequently released from the promotion shortly after.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2014/09/ufc-fight-night-51-results-rani-yahya-gets-revenge-taps-johnny-bedford-in-second|title=UFC Fight Night 51 results: Rani Yahya gets revenge, taps Johnny Bedford in second|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Steven Marrocco|accessdate=2014-09-13|date=2014-09-13}}</ref>\n\n===Grappling===\nOn September 30, 2012, Johnny Bedford competed in a no gi super fight against Jimmy Flick (Flick Brother's MMA) at the American Grappling Federation's Dallas Fall Classic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Z1ka-zKz4A8|title=2012 AGF Dallas Winter Classic - Johnny Bedford (F3) vs Jimmy Flick (Flick Brother's MMA Academy)|publisher=YouTube.com|date=September 30, 2012}}</ref> Johnny won the match by points.\n\n==Bare knuckle boxing==\nBedford faced [[Nick Mamalis]] at a [[Bare Knuckle Fighting Championship|Bare Knuckle FC]] event held on June 2, 2018. He won the fight via TKO in the second round.\n\nOn June 22, 2019, Bedford defeated Reggie Barnett, Jr. via unanimous decision to win BKFC and Police Gazette lightweight titles.\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''Warrior Xtreme Cagefighting'''\n**WXC Bantamweight Championship (One time; current)\n*'''Bare Knuckle FC'''\n**BKFC Lightweight World Champion (current)\n**Police Gazette Lightweight Bare Knuckle title (current)\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n|ko-win